</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="791C2688C1E28615008721013250FA67" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="common names">
<paragraph id="0D6C6F43D0FBD9A91E60BBE70D0507C6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Common names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2057DF5BDC1ECCF93D37481BB6503436" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Candelabrum aloe (English); doringaalwyn, kandelaaraalwyn (Afrikaans); umhlaba (Zulu).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5D6F703A79C48277119801B40F102F72" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="14194A295A940C73101FDF2204409E2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="588B170D2D0E5CC5D9D95606D474C9D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Solitary, arborescent plant up to 2-4 m high. 
<emphasis id="DB0F497B88D182173DED8804D8307E7F" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Stem</emphasis>
simple, erect, 2-4 m high, densely covered with persistent dried leaves. 
<emphasis id="7B3D0B52AE449A9E9920D36BCE686790" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Leaves</emphasis>
densely rosulate, spreading to recurved, dull green to glaucous, without spots, surfaces smooth, lanceolate-ensiform, 
<normalizedToken id="A6980087429E353C59551A255B312A0F" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
100 cm long, 15 cm wide at base, under surface with few spines in median line near apex, occasionally with few scattered spines; margin reddish, cartilaginous, with pungent, reddish to reddish-brown, deltoid teeth, 
<normalizedToken id="1885B155590D4BC3DFFB567C515E1A4A" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
3 mm long, 15-20 mm apart; exudate honey-coloured. 
<emphasis id="736CAC40BDCDBA5CE8734C75ABD50AE8" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Inflorescence</emphasis>
usually single, 
<normalizedToken id="8D88AA094DA5C48567E6E4C55E8B7DA2" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
1 m high, erect, 6- to 12-branched. 
<emphasis id="30C40DD2581C5B38679918F6E180C4C1" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Racemes</emphasis>
cylindrical, slightly acuminate, 50-80 cm long, terminal raceme, the longest and standing out higher than lateral racemes, very dense. 
<emphasis id="517D5D5259CFC508436D7B5B1403754D" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Floral bracts</emphasis>
<normalizedToken id="EA29D91B750F44F71E5603C7450DFB5B" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
10 mm long, 
<normalizedToken id="2B7632775E7617EA5250976310948F4C" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
5 mm wide. 
<emphasis id="45C207D26E51E568B27BC313B0037CB6" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pedicels</emphasis>
6 mm long. 
<emphasis id="1FAA189D60880C0C8AF27896D4B4EECC" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Flowers</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="A3633EEA2236907976F9D1FE1D5A536C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">perianth</emphasis>
scarlet, sometimes rose-pink or orange, rarely white, 
<normalizedToken id="963202DB04A53FD38F27749287921876" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
32 mm long, 
<normalizedToken id="169E5F797518151B8187410FA6995E11" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
5 mm across ovary, widening above ovary towards slightly upturned mouth, clavate-cylindrical, slightly ventricose; outer segments free for 16-22 mm; 
<emphasis id="D4B36A1C3081A37C7459BF6203EDD1BF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">stamens</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="E874F7EDC330A63B286BBD2F12D08894" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">style</emphasis>
exserted 20 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2DF0EA5ABEF1E7EC4780F5BDB121C6B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="flowering time">
<paragraph id="1D2F9A3DD14CE48C2CED0C9C4E159B32" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Flowering time.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D58F93914C8687CBA6ADDE94598ADC8A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">June-July.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3D3A3F85DA18466F4378939694DBABA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="653C6206C2355E4B014487F491C05B21" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC49C9930756A83E54373F37791932F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Thornveld and bushy places on rocky slopes and hills and undulating country.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9864D176DCB8AADDA086A86EBFDEBFFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="E5F57FB80F3A07B26BD378DA44A63DAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D905197BD018F048BCED473B6C782FD3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="D31695CD0C6A15C1E066F977051DD561" authorityName="A. Berger" authorityYear="1906" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe candelabrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candelabrum">
<emphasis id="33B50176F16B0B555B1F5F3139D17187" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe candelabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the other tall often single-stemmed aloes in KwaZulu-Natal (
<taxonomicName id="58601B00DA048FC9AB59DD025B292843" authorityName="A. Berger" authorityYear="1905" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe marlothii" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marlothii">
<emphasis id="AD96CC45C2086E655DBB13C5E3647DE9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe marlothii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="145BB339BC4FAE770F993829C0065B09" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe pluridens" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pluridens">
<emphasis id="A1747054862147803E4C23BF54E4949A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe pluridens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="71FBCCBE58CD2263E03079C787489878" authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1896" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe rupestris" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestris">
<emphasis id="03796B04EB33A3DC96A24833CE80B9DC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe rupestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A9962B4CCB06C126299ACF728489123E" authorityName="Reynolds" authorityYear="1937" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe spectabilis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spectabilis">
<emphasis id="9CB880DD7658C680027FE43B47B858FD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe spectabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7860D66DFCDCCC459F645F7456D78C79" authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1880" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe thraskii" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thraskii">
<emphasis id="9C6EE2A9AC5463E842F921AFC68D50A7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe thraskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with branched inflorescences, by having long (
<normalizedToken id="293A9200B4135F12015C6E780BDF7A4D" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
100 
<normalizedToken id="AAE58A63B509418BC54555C40D4F7965" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
15 cm), spreading to recurved, deeply channelled leaves that sometimes have a few scattered spines on the lower surface and pungent, reddish to reddish-brown marginal teeth. The candelabra-like inflorescence is 6- to 12-branched with erect, very dense, cylindrical, slightly acuminate racemes of 50-80 cm long (the terminal raceme being longer than the lateral ones). Flowers are scarlet, sometimes rose-pink to orange, rarely white and 
<normalizedToken id="7D2F70FD16EFEC2B76625D644FEB82AF" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
32 mm long with white inner segment tips.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F240E78BAAB0FAB8BAD8F2DE37B4EC25" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="C0F43CD88FE0F51D82D407C6552A7648" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CA12A4D6C538672C58E5F00C6F12C5B0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Near-threatened. Threats include habitat loss and degradation owing to silviculture, agriculture (mainly sugarcane) and urban expansion, as well as encroachment by alien invasives and illegal harvesting (L. von Staden pers. comm.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="779396CEF878841867EEE0358D9FF96A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F181DC1EB1C1C95EC400794C47C749AE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="94D10CC3D79C9DC88287220B9BD50F4F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
More or less restricted to the valleys between the Umkhomazi and Umgeni Rivers in KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="33EBE6DB9397BC46423C69BB42D02AA8" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aloe candelabrum. Photo: G. F. Smith." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.142.48365.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/388235" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="159B03BC8F07FFD561B546E61D6C47EA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="BD7366881FC4E0C15DC95166BD79ADB1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="26DC414664EED70A1312CC87BAF61A42" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The 
<emphasis id="425B16E78415E0C1E843732F7845B2FA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Index kewensis</emphasis>
entry (now included in International Plant Names Index, www.ipni.org) for 
<taxonomicName id="FE8AFF9C5CE8D3E9B4694343D4C7431A" authorityName="A. Berger" authorityYear="1906" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe candelabrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candelabrum">
<emphasis id="32CB11CA2F479E9339257D5A353530B2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe candelabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tod. in 
<emphasis id="63867B529B78D79CB5AC238EFD0F2541" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hortus Botanicus Panormitanus</emphasis>
: 46 (1876) is wrong as no such name exists. That reference is to 
<taxonomicName id="062707DB0143C635F9B57B4283BA2A53" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Agave" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Agave candelabrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candelabrum">
<emphasis id="60AC00ED386584A70154D8581B28C8A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agave candelabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tod. in 
<emphasis id="5A72C7EF368E8D44449A56344CC2AB1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hortus Botanicus Panormitanus</emphasis>
: 66 (1876). This agave species is probably a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="EB02A283D8A5B6E8F897216571CD22E9" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Agave" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Agave cantala" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cantala">
<emphasis id="A4CA6E9738714A32D28B6A048099410A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agave cantala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Haw.) Roxb. ex Salm-Dyck (
<bibRefCitation id="E86670F3133021C241F9F2F6C0492CF3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n30.2012.a7" author="Figueiredo, E" journalOrPublisher="Bradleya" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="25 - 32" refId="B13" refString="Figueiredo, E, Smith, GF, 2012. Clarifying the application of the long-confused name Aloe commutata, and the establishment of Aloe x commutata Tod. (Asphodelaceae). Bradleya 30: 25 - 32, DOI: https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n30.2012.a7" title="Clarifying the application of the long-confused name Aloe commutata, and the establishment of Aloe x commutata Tod. (Asphodelaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n30.2012.a7" volume="30" year="2012">Figueiredo and Smith 2012</bibRefCitation>
). The name 
<taxonomicName id="B9B766471BDB53B0BFC27EC306DB583C" authorityName="A. Berger" authorityYear="1906" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe candelabrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candelabrum">
<emphasis id="136883D0BAF56B04F609C9A28C8DC436" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe candelabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A.Berger is thus legitimate and not a later homonym (
<bibRefCitation id="0AA432A77188AF4D9924C5C41B3B579E" author="Reynolds, GW" journalOrPublisher="South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B38" refString="Reynolds, GW, 1950. The Aloes of South Africa. Aloes of South Africa Book Fund, Johannesburg." title="The Aloes of South Africa. Aloes of South Africa Book Fund, Johannesburg." year="1950">Reynolds 1950</bibRefCitation>
) as is often reported (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="C5AA14765A50F673457BD21978C25754" author="Govaerts, R" journalOrPublisher="5, Part 1, Fascicle 1. National Botanical Institute, South Africa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/" refId="B16" refString="Govaerts, R, 2014. World checklist of Xanthorrhoeaceae: Aloe. Facilitated by the Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew. http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/" title="World checklist of Xanthorrhoeaceae: Aloe. Facilitated by the Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." url="http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/" year="2014">Govaerts 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ACB4CC968C3462F369A39EDFBBA8075D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Recognition of 
<taxonomicName id="16E33C9E8BC6756F94FC655F8CB7D6ED" authorityName="A. Berger" authorityYear="1906" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe candelabrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candelabrum">
<emphasis id="F62149441A87B5EEE735E34A02BC0429" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe candelabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="790DBCFB5BE241EBEADAE647164FED31" authorityName="Mill" authorityYear="1768" class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Aloe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aloe ferox" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferox">
<emphasis id="AF2E86E17C9B687C36DF375576ED6527" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aloe ferox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mill. (
<bibRefCitation id="7715651F82DC6954191B5BD5DCAE2ECC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n34.2016.a21" author="Smith, GF" journalOrPublisher="Bradleya" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="59 - 69" refId="B48" refString="Smith, GF, Klopper, RR, Crouch, NR, Figueiredo, E, 2016. Reinstatement of Aloe candelabrum A.Berger (Asphodelaceae: Alooideae), a tree-like aloe of KwaZulu-Natal province, South Africa. Bradleya 34: 59 - 69, DOI: https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n34.2016.a21" title="Reinstatement of Aloe candelabrum A. Berger (Asphodelaceae: Alooideae), a tree-like aloe of KwaZulu-Natal province, South Africa." url="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n34.2016.a21" volume="34" year="2016">Smith et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
